    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you want to solve this issue globally for all JUnit tests then go to <code>Preferences &gt; Java &gt; JUnit</code> and at the top click the checkbox for \"<strong>Add 'ea' to VM arguments when creating new JUnit launch configuration</strong>\" Now Eclipse won't bug you for every <em>new test</em> you want to run. For existing tests you have to remove their's run configurations in <code>Run Configuration &gt; JUnit</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1306229,
      "reputation" : 1581,
      "user_id" : 1255181,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 20,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f8f1496335dc0f2240023cd3f18a03bf?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Waldemar Wosiński",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1255181/waldemar-wosi%c5%84ski"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1360066051,
    "creation_date" : 1360066051,
    "answer_id" : 14707185,
    "question_id" : 5509082,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>On <strong>maven</strong> projects you can run <strong>main method</strong> with auto-magic classpath by:</p>\n\n<pre><code>bash&gt; export MAVEN_OPTS=\"-ea\" &amp;&amp; mvn exec:java -Dexec.mainClass=\"com.your.class.with.main\"\ncmd&gt; set MAVEN_OPTS=\"-ea\" &amp;&amp; mvn exec:java -Dexec.mainClass=\"com.your.class.with.main\"\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>In linux/eclipse you can add terminal window with bash for more convenient use.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 506679,
      "reputation" : 972,
      "user_id" : 1149606,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e29131430ec7d949248d3280cff526ba?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Josef.B",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1149606/josef-b"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 14,
    "last_activity_date" : 1760630378,
    "last_edit_date" : 1760630378,
    "creation_date" : 1399854825,
    "answer_id" : 23599451,
    "question_id" : 5509082,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>To do this globally for all Java runs, edit the Installed JREs properties.</p>\n<p>For example:  Window -&gt; Preferences -&gt; highlight the default JRE -&gt; click Edit... -&gt; In the Default VM arguments input box, enter -ea -&gt; click the Finish button.</p>\n<p>This worked on Eclipse Kepler SR2.</p>\n"
  } ],
